n></div><div class=3D"post-entry"><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">The Gau=
ge. The gauge is a necessary evil for patterns that need to =E2=80=98fit=E2=
=80=99. Sweaters, vests, skirts etc need to have a specific size to fit, so=
 therefore they have a =E2=80=98gauge=E2=80=99. This is one of those elemen=
ts in knitting that HAS TO BE DONE for EVERY PROJECT*, but I find it to be =
the most dreaded aspect of knitting (I may be talking for myself but I have=
 seen others whine about it too). *Some scarves or potholders where size do=
esn=E2=80=99t matter might not have a gauge listed. I=E2=80=99m using ALL C=
APS and the word =E2=80=98EVERY=E2=80=99 to drive home the importance of th=
e gauge. What I=E2=80=99m really saying is: almost all patterns have a gaug=
e. I don=E2=80=99t like to make general categorizations like that but this =
is one of those things that needs to be emphasized.</p><div id=3D"ez-toc-co=
