the-Gauge-for-an-Effective-Swatch"></span><strong>Translating the Gauge for=
 an Effective Swatch</strong><span class=3D"ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2=
><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">The numbers listed on the gauge are what=
 we are ideally shooting for=E2=80=A6 But, when a gauge says to knit X numb=
er of stitches by Y number of rows, we really need to make a larger swatch =
to account for some quirks of knitted fabric. A knitted swatch has a beginn=
ing edge, two side edges and an end edge, each of which influences the knit=
 fabric in some way.</p><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">We want to add in=
 an extra =E2=80=9Cinch=E2=80=9D worth of stitches so that when we measure,=
 we are getting a nice, unaffected area that is not influenced by the edges=
. For example, when a gauge calls for 5 sts per inch and 4 rows per inch, (=
which would normally be 20 sts and 16 rows for a typical 4=E2=80=9D swatch)=
 you should cast on an extra 5 stitches and knit for an extra 4 rows. So yo=
ur adjusted gauge looks like this: 25 sts and 30 rows. You can make the sam=
e adjustment to your gauge, add an inch worth of stitches to the stitch cou=
nt and an inch worth of rows to the recommended row count.</p><p class=3D"h=
