nittingGauge17.jpg" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-4025 lazyload"></figure></di=
v><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size"><strong>Blocking is optional but <em>hi=
ghly recommended</em>.</strong> <em>I have been known to skip the blocking =
on a swatch. Yes, I can be very lazy.</em> I do <strong><em>LOVE</em></stro=
ng> the results, it is the impatient side of me that HATES the process.</p>=
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><span class=3D"ez-toc-section" id=3D"-Workin=
g-a-Swatch-in-the-Round-in-Stockinette-Stitch" ez-toc-data-id=3D"#-Working-=
a-Swatch-in-the-Round-in-Stockinette-Stitch"></span>* Working a Swatch in t=
he Round in Stockinette Stitch<span class=3D"ez-toc-section-end"></span></h=
2><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size"><a class=3D"rank-math-link" href=3D"htt=
ps://www.stitchclinic.com/stockinette-stitch/">See here if you don=E2=80=99=
t know or recall what the Stockinette Stitch is</a>. Our knitting habits ch=
ange if we are knitting flat or in the round. Knitting flat has us doing bo=
th knit and purl stitches. Each is a little different width and height even=
 if you think you are doing it exactly the same. If you are knitting in the=
 round, all of your stitches are knit stitches. All those little bits of le=
ngth add up over hundreds of stitches, which can change your result drastic=
ally.</p><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">A trick to check you are maintai=
ning the length/space between rows, place an item gently in the new loops y=
ou are creating at the beginning of a new row. Keep it there just until you=
 have enough stitches to establish a good tension and the loop doesn=E2=80=
=99t change size. The loop length between rows needs to be wider than the s=
watch so the swatch can be laid flat for measuring.</p><h2 class=3D"wp-bloc=
k-heading"><span class=3D"ez-toc-section" id=3D"What-to-Do-with-Leftover-Sw=
atches" ez-toc-data-id=3D"#What-to-Do-with-Leftover-Swatches"></span><stron=
g>What to Do with Leftover Swatches:</strong><span class=3D"ez-toc-section-=
end"></span></h2><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">1) undo and use yarn in =
project (what I usually do if there is any hesitation about amount of yarn =
needed for a project)<br>2) to hold yarn needles and other items in notions=
 pouch (next best use I=E2=80=99ve found, but you only need so many of thes=
e)<br></p><div class=3D"wp-block-image"><figure class=3D"aligncenter size-l=
arge"><img decoding=3D"async" data-pin-url=3D"https://www.stitchclinic.com/=
knitting-gauge/?tp_image_id=3D4026" data-pin-title=3D"Hey, Swatch It! Begin=
ners Guide to the Knitting Gauge" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQAB=
AIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src=3D"https://www.stitc=
hclinic.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/KnittingGauge18.jpg" alt=3D"" class=
=3D"wp-image-4026 lazyload"></figure></div><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size=
"><br>3) pocket for another project<br>4) pieced together to make a large b=
lanket<br>5) mismatched coasters</p><h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><span cl=
ass=3D"ez-toc-section" id=3D"Other-Considerations-for-Knitting-the-Swatch" =
ez-toc-data-id=3D"#Other-Considerations-for-Knitting-the-Swatch"></span>Oth=
er Considerations for Knitting the Swatch:<span class=3D"ez-toc-section-end=
"></span></h2><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">Do the Math: If you like th=
e fabric the swatch creates but it is not the correct gauge, it is possible=
 to adjust it, it=E2=80=99s just a more advanced skill. The number of stitc=
hes is more important than the number of rows if you need to adjust the pat=
tern. Many patterns call for a length of knitting instead of a number of ro=
ws. If your pattern has measurements, just measure as you go until you have=
 the correct length. Then start your next section.</p><h2 class=3D"wp-block=
-heading"><span class=3D"ez-toc-section" id=3D"Use-Gauge-to-Substitute-Othe=
r-Yarns" ez-toc-data-id=3D"#Use-Gauge-to-Substitute-Other-Yarns"></span><st=
rong>Use Gauge to Substitute Other Yarns</strong><span class=3D"ez-toc-sect=
ion-end"></span></h2><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">Now that you underst=
and how the needle size relates to the yarn weight, we can use that informa=
tion to substitute other yarns in our patterns. When a pattern is published=
, it usually mentions a specific yarn that was used for the garment photogr=
aphed and was extensively tested with the pattern. Some of the older patter=
ns I have list yarns that are no longer being made, are too expensive for m=
e, or I just don=E2=80=99t like=E2=80=A6 so what now?</p><p class=3D"has-me=
dium-font-size">Take a look at the knitting gauge listedon the pattern, the=
n look at the label on yarns you have or yarns you want to buy. See if they=
 can be used interchangeably. Is there a suggested needle size? If you knit=
 up a swatch in this new yarn and it is equivalent to the gauge from the pa=
ttern, you are all set! Even if you have to adjust the needle size once or =
twice, it is well worth the effort.</p><h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><span=
 class=3D"ez-toc-section" id=3D"In-the-End-Only-Kindness-Matters%E2%80%A6" =
ez-toc-data-id=3D"#In-the-End-Only-Kindness-Matters=E2=80=A6"></span><stron=
g>In the End, Only Kindness Matters=E2=80=A6</strong><span class=3D"ez-toc-=
section-end"></span></h2><p class=3D"has-medium-font-size">(Thank you Jewel=
 for these inspiring words, don=E2=80=99t know if you said them first) Be k=
ind to yourself, knit the stinking swatch! You=E2=80=99ll be so glad you di=
d. I swear, knitting a swatch feels like it takes longer than the project b=
ut it is <strong>so worth it</strong>. I=E2=80=99d rather mess up a few inc=
hes of knitting than get to the end of a long, arduous knit and be complete=
ly wrong!</p><h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><span class=3D"ez-toc-section" =
id=3D"Remember-ALWAYS-do-a-TEST-SWATCH-before-starting-a-pattern-even-thoug=
h-it-sucks" ez-toc-data-id=3D"#Remember-ALWAYS-do-a-TEST-SWATCH-before-star=
ting-a-pattern-even-though-it-sucks"></span>Remember, <strong>ALWAYS do a T=
EST SWATCH before starting a pattern <em>even though it sucks!</em></strong=
><span class=3D"ez-toc-section-end"></span></h2><p class=3D"has-medium-font=
-size">If you have any questions about your knitting gauge, please feel fre=
e to ask them in the comment section below or <a class=3D"rank-math-link" h=
ref=3D"mailto:marissa@stitchclinic.com">send me an email: marissa@stitchcli=
nic.com</a>.</p><center><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"lazyload" style=3D=
